 stating, \"it has quickly became obvious that on the pitch \u2014 ultimately where it matters most, of course \u2014 PES simply plays the more satisfying and entertaining game of football [in comparison to ''[[FIFA 10]]''. When it comes to the basic on-pitch action there looks to be a clear winner\".<ref>{{cite news |title=PES 2010 \u2013 how could I ever have doubted you? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/oct/11/games5 |date=2009-10-12 |work=guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited | location=London | first=Greg | last=Howson | accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref> IGN gave the game an 8.7/10, while PSM3 gave the game an 89. GameSpot, however, gave the PS3 and 360 versions a 6.5.\n\n==Other editions==\n\n===''World Soccer: Winning Eleven 2010 - Arcade Championship''===\nOn February 24, 2010, the latest Winning Eleven arcade title was released. Arcade Championship 2010 is the latest entry in the arcade Winning Eleven series, and a followup to Arcade Championship 2008. The game retains many of the features of that title, including nationwide online play and the ability to use PlayStation 2 controllers. PlayStation 3 controllers are supported as well, although only in some cabinets. Outside of a major leap in visuals, updates include 300 added motions, the ability to dribble in all directions, and an update in team count to around 230. New systems include the Icon Chat System for simple communication during matches, and a Real Time Player Substitution system which lets you specify player substitutions whenever you like. These systems use the game's touch screen. The game also includes a Tag Play mode. Two players can use two cabinets to control a single team together. Following the match, the game gives you a \"Sychro Rate,\" indicating your compatibility. Konami will be holding an in-game tournament using the Competition Mode to coincide with the UEFA Champions League tournament. The schedule for the in-game tournament is being worked to match the real tournament.<ref>http://www.andriasang.com/e/blog/2010/02/24/winning_eleven_dual_shock/</ref>\n\n===''World Soccer: Winning Eleven 2010 - Aoki Samurai no Chousen''===\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = World Soccer: Winning Eleven 2010 - Aoki Samurai no Chousen\n| image =\n| developer = Konami Computer Entertainment Tokyo\n| publisher = [[Konami]]\n| designer = Shingo 'Seabass' Takatsuka (executive)<br />Naoya Hatsumi (producer)<br />Toru Nagai (artistic director)<br />Satoshi Suzuki (game mechanics director)\n| engine =\n|released = {{vgrelease|JP|20 May 2010}}<ref>http://www.play-asia.com/paOS-13-71-bp-49-en-15-World+Soccer+Winning+Eleven+2010%3A+Aoki+Samurai+no+Chousen-70-3sct.html</ref>\n| series = ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer]]''\n| genre = [[Sports game|Sports]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[Multiplayer]]\n| platforms = [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation Portable]] and [[Wii]]\n}}\nOn 3 February 2010, Konami announced that it will release ''World Soccer: Winning Eleven 2010 - Aoki Samurai no Chousen'' - translated to Challenge of Blue Samurai. (stylised ''WORLD SOCCER Winning Eleven 2010 Aoki Samurai no Chousen'') in spring 2010 for PlayStation 3, PlayStation 2, PlayStation Portable and Wii. The new title is the latest installment in the Winning Eleven series which has sold over 56 million copies (as of September 2009) worldwide. In Aoki Samurai no Chosen players can join the Japanese national team as it goes toe-to-toe against the top teams from around the world in a bid to be crowned world champion. Officially licensed by the Japan Football Association, the new release features the biggest names in Japanese soccer sporting their national team uniforms. The new title builds on the excitement generated during this official \"Year of Sports\" in Japan and is sure to score a major goal with soccer fans across the country.<ref>http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.co.jp/en/news/release/2010/0203_2/index.html</ref> The game will be an expanded version of the current PES 2010 game having the same AI engine. The game is set to be released on May 20, 2010.<ref>http://www.konami.jp/we/2010/blue/ps3/</ref><ref>http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/winning-eleven-wc-new-details-and-screens-hit/</ref>\n'''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pesgalaxy.com/ Generally PES Unofficial News & Updates Blog / Forums]\n*[http://forum.zockerfront.de/ Unofficial PES Discussion & Editing Forums ]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZxI-vPCt9dI Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 (YouTube)]\n\n{{Pro Evolution Soccer}}\n\n[[Category:2009 video games]]\n[[Category:Games for Windows certified games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Mobile games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Portable games]]\n[[Category:Pro Evolution Soccer]]\n[[Category:Sports video games with career mode]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Wii games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Pro Evolution Soccer 2010\n| image = [[File:PES 2010 UK Cover.jpg|250px]]<br>[[United Kingdom|UK]] cover art featuring (from left to right) [[Lionel Messi]] and [[Fernando Torres]]\n| developer = Konami Computer Entertainment Tokyo\n| publisher = [[Konami]]\n| designer = Dhanush Mahendran (executive)<br />Naoya Hatsumi (producer)<br />Toru Nagai (artistic director)<br />Satoshi Suzuki (game mechanics director)<br />Jon Murphy (European team leader)\n| engine =joursaint\n|released = {{collapsible list|title=23 October 2009|'''PS3<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 Release Information for PlayStation 3 |url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/console/ps3/data/959291.html |work=gamefaqs.com |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |accessdate=2009-09-25}}</ref> and Xbox 360'''<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 Release Information for Xbox 360 |url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/console/xbox360/data/959290.html |work=gamefaqs.com |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |accessdate=2009-09-25}}</ref><br />{{vgrelease|EU|23 October 2009|AUS|29 October 2009}}{{vgrelease|NA|3 November 2009}}{{vgrelease|JP|5 November 2009}}'''PC'''<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 Release Information for PC |url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/computer/doswin/data/959292.html |work=gamefaqs.com |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |accessdate=2009-09-25}}</ref><br />{{vgrelease|EU|23 October 2009|AUS|29 October 2009}}{{vgrelease|NA|31 December 2009}}'''PSP'''<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 Release Information for PSP |url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/portable/psp/data/959293.html |work=gamefaqs.com |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |accessdate=2009-09-25}}</ref><br />{{vgrelease|EU|6 November 2009}}{{vgrelease|NA|10 November 2009}}'''PS2'''<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 Release Information for PlayStation 2 |url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/console/ps2/data/959294.html |work=gamefaqs.com |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |accessdate=2009-09-25}}</ref><br />{{vgrelease|EU|6 November 2009}}{{vgrelease|NA|10 November 2009|AUS|12 November 2009}}'''Wii'''<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 Release Information for Wii |url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/console/wii/data/960815.html |work=gamefaqs.com |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |accessdate=2009-09-25}}</ref><br />{{vgrelease|NA|10 November 2009|EU|20 November 2009|AUS|3 December 2009}}}}\n| series = ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer]]''\n| genre = [[Sports game|Sports]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]<br>[[PlayStation 2]]<br>[[PlayStation 3]]<br>[[PlayStation Portable]]<br>[[Xbox 360]]<br>[[iOS]]<br>[[Wii]]<br>[[Mobile Phone]]\n}}\n\n'''''Pro Evolution Soccer 2010''''' (officially abbreviated as '''''PES 2010''''' and known in Asia as '''''World Soccer: Winning Eleven 2010''''') is the ninth [[Association football|football]] video game in the ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer]]'' series. The game was developed and published by [[Konami]] for release on [[Sony]]'s [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation 3]], and [[PlayStation Portable]]; [[Microsoft]]'s [[Xbox 360]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]; [[Nintendo]]'s [[Wii]]; and [[mobile phone]]s.<ref name=\"PES 2010\">{{cite web |title=PES 2010: New Season, All New Game |url=http://uk.games.konami-europe.com/news.do?idNews=396 |date=2009-04-08 |work=konami-europe.com |publisher=Konami Digital Entertainment |accessdate=2009-08-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930183546/http://uk.games.konami-europe.com/news.do?idNews=396 |archivedate=2009-09-30 }}</ref>\n\n''PES 2010'' was announced on 8 April 2009<ref name=\"PES 2010\" /> and the playable demo for the PC, PS3, and Xbox 360 versions was released on 17 September 2009.<ref>{{cite web |title=PES 2010 Demo available on XBLA / PSN / PC on September 17th |url=http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/pes2010-demo-available-on-xbla-psn-pc-on-september-17th/ |date=2009-09-16 |work=winningelevenblog.com |publisher=self-published |accessdate=2009-09-16}}</ref> The game itself was released on 23 October 2009 in Europe.\n\n[[Lionel Messi]] ([[FC Barcelona]] and Argentine player) is a key endorsement player for ''PES 2010'', having featured extensively throughout the promotion and development of the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Messi E3 Trailer + Screenshots |url=http://www.pesfan.com/news/8165753/?widget_konami=1#news |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090607001806/http://www.pesfan.com/news/8165753/?widget_konami=1#news |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-06-07 |work=pesfan.com |publisher=PESFan |accessdate=2009-08-24 }}</ref> He features on the cover alongside [[Fernando Torres]] (Spanish and [[Liverpool F.C.]] player), another endorsement player.<ref>{{cite web |title=Torres signs for PES 2010 |url=http://www.videogamer.com/news/torres_signs_for_pes_2010.html |date=2009-06-23 |work=videogamer.com |publisher=Pro-G Media |accessdate=2009-08-24}}</ref> ''PES 2010'' was succeeded by ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer 2011]]''.\n\nThe game was released on the [[iPhone OS]] in June 2010.<ref>http://uk.games.konami-europe.com/mobile/iphoneNews.do?idNews=486</ref>\n\n==Features==\n''PES 2010'' has the following features.<ref name=\"PES 2010\" />\n* ''PES 2010'' contains improved visuals, animations and moves, including live player expressions and movements that will change according to conditions on the field. Animations of dribbling and shots on goal, as well as individual skills, have all been reworked.\n* Gameplay has been made more realistic. This includes more versatile goalkeepers and greater control over penalties in terms of placing and accuracy.\n* There will be an enhanced online experience: a new development team is solely dedicated to improving online play and other aspects, such as downloadable content and more updates.\n* The A.I. has been improved thanks to Teamvision 2.0. Referees have been reworked to make more balanced calls during matches.\n* ''PES 2010'' introduces greater strategy control: various strategic elements, such as pass frequency and width of play, can be altered.\n* The match-day atmosphere gives a better taste of home and away crowds, which will react spontaneously to all the action on the pitch.\n* Master League has been enhanced. It has improved managerial aspects, resulting in an increased managerial career lifespan.\n* 360-degree control is introduced, available on the PC, PS3, and Xbox 360 versions of the game via the analog sticks on the respective controllers. PS3 owners will also benefit from this when using the [[DualShock]]'s D-Pad, but the Wii D-Pad is limited to eight-directional control and the Xbox 360 D-Pad to sixteen-directional control due to their hardware.\n\n==Content==\nWith an exclusive deal with [[UEFA]], both the [[UEFA Champions League]] and (for the first time) the [[UEFA Europa League]] are fully licensed.<ref name=\"PES 2010\" /> The tournaments are integrated into the Master League mode;<ref>{{cite web |title=OPM France Confirms CL Integration |url=http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/opm-france-confirms-cl-intergration/ |date=2009-05-03 |work=winningelevenblog.com |publisher=self-published |accessdate=2009-08-24}}</ref> however, the Europa League is only available on the PC, PS3 and Xbox 360 versions.\n\nDouble Fusion signed an agreement with Konami for advertising their clients products in the game.<ref>{{cite web |title=Double Fusion signs in-game advertising agreement with Konami Digital Entertainment for PES 2010 |url=http://www.doublefusion.com/press/html/Konami_PES_20_04_09.html |date=2009-04-20 |work=doublefusion.com |publisher=Double Fusion |accessdate=2009-08-24}}</ref>\n\nIn total, the game includes 258 squads, with 139 of them being officially licensed. Including the empty league, the game has a total of 55 teams that can be changed completely by user editing.<ref>{{cite web |title=PES 2010: Edit Mode |url=http://www.thesportsgamer.com/?p=447 |date=2009-11-05 |work=thesportsgamer.com |publisher=TSG: The Sports Gamer |accessdate=2009-11-05}}</ref>\n\nLike previous versions, there is also a separate league with 18 empty teams (Team A, Team B, etc.), each of which can be edited fully. This was initially introduced when Konami failed to get the rights to the German [[Fu\u00dfball-Bundesliga|Bundesliga]]. Since its introduction, it has become very popular amongst the ''PES'' community, and as a result, they are usually made into the Bundesliga or another league of one's preference by patch makers. Popular made leagues are the [[Liga Sagres]], [[Belgian First Division A]], [[Football League Championship|Championship]], [[EFL League One]], [[EFL League Two]] [[Liga I]], [[Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] or [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de M\u00e9xico]], Greek Superleague and Moroccan Botola Pro.\n\n===Commentators===\n* [[Jon Champion]] and [[Mark Lawrenson]] provide the English commentary.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pjedsikan JES jed 2010 \u2013 England vs Brazil Highlights |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SQLk5_KLQDc&feature=player_embedded# |date=2009-10-10 |work=youtube.com |publisher=self-published |accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref>\n* Gregoire Margotton and [[Christophe Dugarry]] provide the French commentary.\n* Wolff-Christoph Fuss and Hansi K\u00fcpper provide the German commentary.\n* [[Jon Kabira]] and [[Tsuyoshi Kitazawa]] provide the Japanese commentary.\n* Carlos Mart\u00ednez and Julio Maldonado provide the Spanish commentary for Spain.\n* Pierluigi Pardo and [[Jos\u00e9 Altafini]] provide the Italian commentary.\n* Pedro Sousa and Lu\u00eds Freitas Lobo provide the Portuguese commentary for Portugal.\n* Christian Martinoli and Luis Garc\u00eda provide the Spanish commentary for Latin America.\n\n==Updates==\n\n===Version 1.01===\nOn 22 October 2009, the first patch for the PC, PS3, and Xbox 360 versions of the game was released between 10:00 and 12:00 (GMT). The \"Legends,\" \"Community,\" and \"Competition\" online modes were added.<ref>{{cite web |title=2009.10.22 New patch file released |url=http://www.maintemgr.konamistyle.jp/mds/2.0/client/web_pes2010/detail.php?os=o&pid=ps3&did=uk&mid=5247 |date=2009-10-22 |work=konamistyle.jp |publisher=Konami Digital Entertainment |accessdate=2009-10-22}}</ref>\n\n===Version 1.02===\nOn 9 November 2009, a patch for ''World Soccer: Winning Eleven 2010'' was released at 6:00 (GMT). The patch updated the Japan national team kits and various team squads.<ref>{{cite web |title=PES 2010 Update Out Thursday? |url=http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/pes-2010-update-out-thursday/ |date=2009-11-07 |work=winningelevenblog.com |publisher=self-published |accessdate=2009-11-17}}</ref> A patch for ''PES 2010'' was released on 17 November 2009, which fixes the problem of edit data reverting to default when content is downloaded.<ref>{{cite web |title=PES 2010 1.02 Update Hits |url=http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/pes-2010-1-02-update-hits/ |date=2009-11-17 |work=winningelevenblog.com |publisher=self-published |accessdate=2009-11-17}}</ref> On 24 November 2009, another patch for ''PES 2010'' was released, including graphical additions and a roster update.<ref>{{cite web |title=PES 2010 Update Launches! |url=http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/pes-2010-update-launches/ |date=2009-11-24 |work=winningelevenblog.com |publisher=self-published |accessdate=2009-11-24}}</ref>\n\n===Version 1.03===\nThe update makes the game's formation settings easier to use, and also adds icons to show the connectivity status of online players. All settings can now be saved and stocked data will be loaded automatically, speeding up play immediately. Likewise, the new connectivity icons will show the user as a grey icon, with green, yellow, and red icons detailing the quality of the opponent's connection, with red being the worse. The update also improves match making between users of the PC-DVD version of the game with different processors.<ref>http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/new-patch-dlc-hits/</ref>\n\n===Version 1.04 & 1.05===\nThe new update was released on 16 February 2010 for PlayStation 3, Xbox 360 and PC. The latest update files brings every club team roster in line with all changes and transfers made up to 15 January. Some player parameters were updated in line with their performance in the first half of the season and a new boot design was included.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pesfan.com/news/8813450/New-PES-2010-DLC-Announced/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120919083651/http://www.pesfan.com/news/8813450/New-PES-2010-DLC-Announced/ |archivedate=2012-09-19 }}</ref><ref>http://www.maintemgr.konamistyle.jp/mds/2.0/client/web_pes2010/detail.php?os=o&pid=ps3&did=uk&mid=5880</ref> However, when implementing the new Download Contents, all save data created before the update remained with certain Edit Data reverting to default. Player and team data will remain edited, while player registration and formation data will revert to Default. Deleting the Download contents from the system menu will invalidate any save data created after its implementation.<ref>http://www.maintemgr.konamistyle.jp/mds/2.0/client/web_pes2010/detail.php?os=o&pid=ps3&did=uk&mid=5881</ref>\n\nIt was revealed on 17 February 2010 that the new update contained incorrect data, and some players' free kick motion do not appear properly. When any of these players are used in a match, the game may not perform properly, and ''PES'' would like the player to refrain from using these players until the problem is addressed. ''PES'' are currently in preparation for releasing the corrected data, which will address the problem once it is applied to the game, and they would like to ask the player not to remove any game data. They are making every effort to release the corrected data later this week, and the schedule will be announced once fixed. They sincerely apologize for any inconveniences caused by this problem.<ref>http://www.maintemgr.konamistyle.jp/mds/2.0/client/web_pes2010/detail.php?os=o&pid=ps3&did=uk&mid=5898</ref>\n\nOn 19 February 2010, a fixed version of the update was released, concerning the inadequate free kick motion, and included a newer better transfer update.<ref>http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/dlc-fix-released/</ref>\n\n===Version 1.06===\nThe update includes new UEFA Champions League Final Madrid 2010 ball, new ADIDAS F50 Tunit boots and some tweaking to the rosters.<ref>http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/new-pes-2010-dlc-hits/</ref>\n\n===Version 1.07===\nAn update containing various new international kits was released on June 8. It contained updated squads for some international teams, except: Brazil, Argentina, Germany and the Netherlands.\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| state = collapsed\n<!-- Aggregators -->\n| MC = PS3: 78/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-3/pro-evolution-soccer-2010 |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 for PlayStation 3 Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-08-25}}</ref><br />X360: 78/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/pro-evolution-soccer-2010 |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 for Xbox 360 Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-08-25}}</ref><br />PC: 78/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/pro-evolution-soccer-2010 |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 for PC Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-08-25}}</ref><br />PSP: 72/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/psp/pro-evolution-soccer-2010 |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 for PSP Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-08-25}}</ref><br />WII: 82/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/wii/pro-evolution-soccer-2010 |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 for Wii Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-08-25}}</ref><br />iOS: 75/100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/ios/pro-evolution-soccer-2010-us |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 (US) for iPhone/iPad Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-08-25}}</ref>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| 1UP = B\u2212<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 Review for the PS3,Xbox 360 |url=http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3176913&p=37 |date=2009-11-13 |work=1up.com |publisher=UGO Entertainment |accessdate=2009-11-13}}</ref>\n| EuroG = 7/10<ref>{{cite web |title=PES 2010: Pro Evolution Soccer Review |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/pes-2010-pro-evolution-soccer-review? |date=2009-10-15 |work=eurogamer.net |publisher=Eurogamer Network Ltd. |accessdate=2009-10-16}}</ref>\n| GSpot = 6.5/10<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 Review for PlayStation 3 |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/ps3/sports/proevolutionsoccer2010/review.html |date=2009-10-28 |work=gamespot.com |publisher=CBS Interactive Inc. |accessdate=2009-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091102041626/http://uk.gamespot.com/ps3/sports/proevolutionsoccer2010/review.html |archive-date=2009-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| IGN = 8.7/10.0<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 Review |url=http://uk.ps3.ign.com/articles/103/1035329p1.html |date=2009-10-15 |work=ign.com |publisher=IGN Entertainment, Inc |accessdate=2009-10-17}}</ref>\n| PSM3 = 89/100<ref>{{cite journal |date=November 2009 |journal=PlayStation 3 Magazine UK |pages=72}}</ref>\n| VG = 7/10<ref>{{cite web |title=PES 2010 Review for PS3 |url=http://www.videogamer.com/ps3/pes_2010/review.html |date=2009-10-15 |work=videogamer.com |publisher=Pro-G Media Ltd. |accessdate=2009-10-17}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Critical response===\nThe game has received positive reviews. Greg Howson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave PES 2010 a favourable review, stating, \"it has quickly became obvious that on the pitch \u2014 ultimately where it matters most, of course \u2014 PES simply plays the more satisfying and entertaining game of football [in comparison to ''[[FIFA 10]]''. When it comes to the basic on-pitch action there looks to be a clear winner\".<ref>{{cite news |title=PES 2010 \u2013 how could I ever have doubted you? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/oct/11/games5 |date=2009-10-12 |work=guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited | location=London | first=Greg | last=Howson | accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref> IGN gave the game an 8.7/10, while PSM3 gave the game an 89. GameSpot, however, gave the PS3 and 360 versions a 6.5.\n\n==Other editions==\n\n===''World Soccer: Winning Eleven 2010 - Arcade Championship''===\nOn February 24, 2010, the latest Winning Eleven arcade title was released. Arcade Championship 2010 is the latest entry in the arcade Winning Eleven series, and a followup to Arcade Championship 2008. The game retains many of the features of that title, including nationwide online play and the ability to use PlayStation 2 controllers. PlayStation 3 controllers are supported as well, although only in some cabinets. Outside of a major leap in visuals, updates include 300 added motions, the ability to dribble in all directions, and an update in team count to around 230. New systems include the Icon Chat System for simple communication during matches, and a Real Time Player Substitution system which lets you specify player substitutions whenever you like. These systems use the game's touch screen. The game also includes a Tag Play mode. Two players can use two cabinets to control a single team together. Following the match, the game gives you a \"Sychro Rate,\" indicating your compatibility. Konami will be holding an in-game tournament using the Competition Mode to coincide with the UEFA Champions League tournament. The schedule for the in-game tournament is being worked to match the real tournament.<ref>http://www.andriasang.com/e/blog/2010/02/24/winning_eleven_dual_shock/</ref>\n\n===''World Soccer: Winning Eleven 2010 - Aoki Samurai no Chousen''===\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = World Soccer: Winning Eleven 2010 - Aoki Samurai no Chousen\n| image =\n| developer = Konami Computer Entertainment Tokyo\n| publisher = [[Konami]]\n| designer = Shingo 'Seabass' Takatsuka (executive)<br />Naoya Hatsumi (producer)<br />Toru Nagai (artistic director)<br />Satoshi Suzuki (game mechanics director)\n| engine =\n|released = {{vgrelease|JP|20 May 2010}}<ref>http://www.play-asia.com/paOS-13-71-bp-49-en-15-World+Soccer+Winning+Eleven+2010%3A+Aoki+Samurai+no+Chousen-70-3sct.html</ref>\n| series = ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer]]''\n| genre = [[Sports game|Sports]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[Multiplayer]]\n| platforms = [[PlayStation 2]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation Portable]] and [[Wii]]\n}}\nOn 3 February 2010, Konami announced that it will release ''World Soccer: Winning Eleven 2010 - Aoki Samurai no Chousen'' - translated to Challenge of Blue Samurai. (stylised ''WORLD SOCCER Winning Eleven 2010 Aoki Samurai no Chousen'') in spring 2010 for PlayStation 3, PlayStation 2, PlayStation Portable and Wii. The new title is the latest installment in the Winning Eleven series which has sold over 56 million copies (as of September 2009) worldwide. In Aoki Samurai no Chosen players can join the Japanese national team as it goes toe-to-toe against the top teams from around the world in a bid to be crowned world champion. Officially licensed by the Japan Football Association, the new release features the biggest names in Japanese soccer sporting their national team uniforms. The new title builds on the excitement generated during this official \"Year of Sports\" in Japan and is sure to score a major goal with soccer fans across the country.<ref>http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.co.jp/en/news/release/2010/0203_2/index.html</ref> The game will be an expanded version of the current PES 2010 game having the same AI engine. The game is set to be released on May 20, 2010.<ref>http://www.konami.jp/we/2010/blue/ps3/</ref><ref>http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/winning-eleven-wc-new-details-and-screens-hit/</ref>\n'''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pesgalaxy.com/ Generally PES Unofficial News & Updates Blog / Forums]\n*[http://forum.zockerfront.de/ Unofficial PES Discussion & Editing Forums ]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZxI-vPCt9dI Pro Evolution Soccer 2010 (YouTube)]\n\n{{Pro Evolution Soccer}}\n\n[[Category:2009 video games]]\n[[Category:Games for Windows certified games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Mobile games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Portable games]]\n[[Category:Pro Evolution Soccer]]\n[[Category:Sports video games with career mode]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Wii games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n", "name_user": "Joseph2302", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCommentators:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pro_Evolution_Soccer_2010"}
{"title_page": "Axamb language", "text_new": "{{short description|Austronesian language spoken in Vanuatu}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Ahamb\n|states=[[Vanuatu]]\n|region=South [[Malekula]]\n|speakers=950 \n|date=2017\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]]\n|fam4=[[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic]]\n|fam5=[[Central Vanuatu languages|Central Vanuatu]]\n|fam6=[[Malakula languages|Malakula]]\n|fam7=Eastern\n|iso3=ahb\n|glotto=axam1237\n|glottoname=Axamb\n}}\n\n'''Ahamb''', also spelled '''Axamb''' or '''Akhamb''' is an [[Oceanic languages|Oceanic language]] spoken in South [[Malakula]], [[Vanuatu]].\nAhamb has around 1000 speakers, most of whom reside on the small low-lying Ahamb Island and the nearby Malekula mainland. The language is endangered due to a number of factors,<ref>[http://www.elpublishing.org/docs/1/16/ldd16_04.pdf]</ref> including climate change and environmental factors.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.elpublishing.org/docs/1/16/ldd16_04.pdf Ahamb (Malekula, Vanuatu) - Language Contexts]\n*[https://elar.soas.ac.uk/Collection/MPI1042304 ELAR archive collection of recordings of Ahamb speech]\n*[https://icphs2019.org/icphs2019-fullpapers/pdf/full-paper_973.pdf The bilabial trills of Ahamb (Vanuatu): Acoustic and articulatory properties]\n*[http://search.language-archives.org/search.html?fq=subject_language_facet%3A%22Axamb%22 Axamb resources in the OLAC Language Catalog]\n*[http://www.worldcat.org/search?qt=worldcat_org_all&q=axamb Axamb resources in WorldCat]\n*[http://paradisec.org.au/fieldnotes/image_viewer.htm?VAXA106,2 The Story of the Reef Numbur in Ahamb and English]\n*[http://paradisec.org.au/fieldnotes/image_viewer.htm?VAXA108,9 Ahamb phrases and texts, 1999]\n\n{{Languages of Vanuatu}}\n{{Southern Oceanic languages}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Malekula languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Vanuatu]]\n\n\n{{SOceanic-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Austronesian language spoken in Vanuatu}}\n{{Infobox language\n|name=Ahamb\n|region=South [[Malekula]], [[Vanuatu]]\n|speakers=950 \n|date=2017\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]]\n|fam4=[[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic]]\n|fam5=[[Central Vanuatu languages|Central Vanuatu]]\n|fam6=[[Malakula languages|Malakula]]\n|fam7=Eastern\n|iso3=ahb\n|glotto=axam1237\n|glottoname=Axamb\n}}\n\n'''Ahamb''', also spelled '''Axamb''' or '''Akhamb''' is an [[Oceanic languages|Oceanic language]] spoken in South [[Malakula]], [[Vanuatu]].\nAhamb has around 1000 speakers, most of whom reside on the small low-lying Ahamb Island and the nearby Malekula mainland. The language is endangered due to a number of factors,<ref>[http://www.elpublishing.org/docs/1/16/ldd16_04.pdf]</ref> including climate change and environmental factors.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.elpublishing.org/docs/1/16/ldd16_04.pdf Ahamb (Malekula, Vanuatu) - Language Contexts]\n*[https://elar.soas.ac.uk/Collection/MPI1042304 ELAR archive collection of recordings of Ahamb speech]\n*[https://icphs2019.org/icphs2019-fullpapers/pdf/full-paper_973.pdf The bilabial trills of Ahamb (Vanuatu): Acoustic and articulatory properties]\n*[http://search.language-archives.org/search.html?fq=subject_language_facet%3A%22Axamb%22 Axamb resources in the OLAC Language Catalog]\n*[http://www.worldcat.org/search?qt=worldcat_org_all&q=axamb Axamb resources in WorldCat]\n*[http://paradisec.org.au/fieldnotes/image_viewer.htm?VAXA106,2 The Story of the Reef Numbur in Ahamb and English]\n*[http://paradisec.org.au/fieldnotes/image_viewer.htm?VAXA108,9 Ahamb phrases and texts, 1999]\n\n{{Languages of Vanuatu}}\n{{Southern Oceanic languages}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Malekula languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Vanuatu]]\n\n\n{{SOceanic-lang-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Austronesier", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axamb_language"}
{"title_page": "Equestrian at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Team dressage", "text_new": "{{short description|Equestrian at the Olympics}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Team dressage\n|games = 1952 Summer \n|image = \n|caption = \n|venue = [[Ruskeasuo|Ruskeasuo Equestrian Hall]]\n|date = 28\u201329 July\n|competitors = 24\n|nations = 8\n|gold = [[Gustaf Adolf Boltenstern, Jr.]]<br />[[Gehn\u00e4ll Persson]]<br />[[Henri Saint Cyr]]\n|goldNOC = SWE\n|silver = [[Gustav Fischer (equestrian)|Gustav Fischer]]<br />[[Gottfried Trachsel]]<br />[[Henri Chammartin]]\n|silverNOC = SUI\n|bronze = [[Fritz Thiedemann]]<br />[[Ida von Nagel]]<br />[[Heinz Pollay]]\n|bronzeNOC = GER\n|prev = [[Equestrian at the 1948 Summer Olympics \u2013 Team dressage|1948]]\n|next = [[Equestrian at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Team dressage|1956]]\n}}\n{{Equestrian at the 1952 Summer Olympics}}\nThe '''team dressage''' at the '''[[1952 Summer Olympics]]''' took place between 28 and 29 July at the [[Ruskeasuo]] Equestrian Hall. The event was open to women for the first time; of the 24 riders, 2 were female\u2014including one member of the bronze medalist German team, [[Ida von Nagel]]. \n\n==Competition format==\nThe team and individual dressage competitions used the same results. Competitors were given 15 minutes to complete their corresponding tests. For each second over the 15-minute mark, contestants lost half a point. Each team was ranked according to the total scores from their three members.\n\n==Results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Rank\n!Nation\n!Rider\n!Horse\n!Individual Score\n!Team Score\n|-\n| {{gold01}}\n|align=left| {{flagIOC|SWE|1952 Summer}} \n|align=left| [[Henri Saint Cyr]] <br> [[Gustaf Adolf Boltenstern, Jr.]] <br> [[Gehn\u00e4ll Persson]]\n|align=left| Master Rufus <br> Krest <br> Knaust\n| 561.0 <br> 531.0 <br> 505.5\n| '''1597.5'''\n|-\n| {{silver02}}\n|align=left| {{flagIOC|SUI|1952 Summer}}\n|align=left| [[Gottfried Trachsel]] <br> [[Henri Chammartin]] <br> [[Gustav Fischer (equestrian)|Gustav Fischer]]\n|align=left| Kursus <br> W\u00f6hler <br> Soliman\n| 531.0 <br> 529.5 <br> 518.5\n| '''1579.0'''\n|-\n| {{bronze03}}\n|align=left| {{flagIOC|GER|1952 Summer}}\n|align=left| [[Heinz Pollay]] <br> [[Ida von Nagel]] <br> [[Fritz Thiedemann]]\n|align=left| Adular <br> Afrika <br> Chronist\n| 518.5 <br> 503.0 <br> 479.5\n| '''1501.0'''\n|-\n| 4\n|align=left| {{flagIOC|FRA|1952 Summer}}\n|align=left| [[Andr\u00e9 Jousseaume]] <br> [[Jean Peitevin de Saint Andr\u00e9]] <br> [[Jean Saint-Fort Paillard]]\n|align=left| Harpagon <br> Vol au Vent <br> Tapir\n| 541.0 <br> 479.0 <br> 403.5\n| '''1423.5'''\n|-\n| 5\n|align=left| {{flagIOC|CHI|1952 Summer}}\n|align=left| [[Jos\u00e9 Larra\u00edn]] <br> [[H\u00e9ctor Clavel]] <br> [[Ernesto Silva]]\n|align=left| Rey de Oros <br> Frontalera <br> Viarregio\n| 473.5 <br> 452.0 <br> 415.0\n| '''1340.5'''\n|-\n| 6\n|align=left| {{flagIOC|USA|1952 Summer}}\n|align=left| [[Bob Borg]] <br> [[Marjorie Haines]] <br> [[Hartmann Pauly]]\n|align=left| Bill Biddle <br> The Flying Dutchman <br> Reno Overdo\n| 492.0 <br> 446.0 <br> 315.5\n| '''1253.5'''\n|-\n| 7\n|align=left| {{flagIOC|URS|1952 Summer}}\n|align=left| [[Vladimir Raspopov]] <br> [[Vasily Tikhonov (equestrian)|Vasily Tikhonov]] <br> [[Nikolay Sitko]]\n|align=left| Imeninnik <br> Pevec <br> Cesar\n| 433.5 <br> 395.0 <br> 377.0\n| '''1205.5'''\n|-\n| 8\n|align=left| {{flagIOC|POR|1952 Summer}}\n|align=left| [[Ant\u00f3nio Reym\u00e3o Nogueira]] <br> [[Francisco Valadas J\u00fanior]] <br> [[Fernando Paes]]\n|align=left| Napeiro <br> Feitico <br> Matamas\n| 428.5 <br> 422.0 <br> 346.0\n| '''1196.5'''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080411091045/http://www.la84foundation.org/6oic/OfficialReports/1952/OR1952.pdf Official Olympic Report], ''la84.org''.\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Equestrian Team Dressage}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Equestrian At The 1952 Summer Olympics - Team Dressage}}\n[[Category:Equestrian at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Equestrian at the Olympics}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox Olympic event\n|event = Team dressage\n|games = 1952 Summer \n|image = \n|caption = \n|venue = [[Ruskeasuo|Ruskeasuo Equestrian Hall]]\n|date = 28\u201329 July\n|competitors = 24\n|nations = 8\n|gold = [[Gustaf Adolf Boltenstern, Jr.]]<br />[[Gehn\u00e4ll Persson]]<br />[[Henri Saint Cyr]]\n|goldNOC = SWE\n|silver = [[Gustav Fischer (equestrian)|Gustav Fischer]]<br />[[Gottfried Trachsel]]<br />[[Henri Chammartin]]\n|silverNOC = SUI\n|bronze = [[Fritz Thiedemann]]<br />[[Ida von Nagel]]<br />[[Heinz Pollay]]\n|bronzeNOC = GER\n|prev = [[Equestrian at the 1948 Summer Olympics \u2013 Team dressage|1948]]\n|next = [[Equestrian at the 1956 Summer Olympics \u2013 Team dressage|1956]]\n}}\n{{Equestrian at the 1952 Summer Olympics}}\nThe '''team dressage''' at the '''[[1952 Summer Olympics]]''' took place between 28 and 29 July at the [[Ruskeasuo]] Equestrian Hall. The event was open to women for the first time; of the 24 riders, 2 were female\u2014including one member of the bronze medalist German team, [[Ida von Nagel]]. \n\n==Competition format==\nThe team and individual dressage competitions used the same results. Competitors were given 15 minutes to complete their corresponding tests. For each second over the 15-minute mark, contestants lost half a point. Each team was ranked according to the total scores from their three members.\n\n==Results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Rank\n!Nation\n!Rider\n!Horse\n!Individual Score\n!Team Score\n|-\n| {{gold01}}\n|align=left| {{flagIOC|SWE|1952 Summer}} \n|align=left| [[Henri Saint Cyr]] <br> [[Gustaf Adolf Boltenstern, Jr.]] <br> [[Gehn\u00e4ll Persson]]\n|align=left| Master Rufus <br> Krest <br> Knaust\n| 561.0 <br> 531.0 <br> 505.5\n| '''1597.5'''\n|-\n| {{silver02}}\n|align=left| {{flagIOC|SUI|1952 S